The IDP was the difference.

34
03:18:00,000 --> 03:24:00,000

35
03:24:00,000 --> 03:30:00,000
Now let me tell you what an Internal Developer Platform actually is.

36
03:30:00,000 --> 03:36:00,000
There are many definitions. Most of them are vague.
Here is the one that matters for this course.

37
03:36:00,000 --> 03:42:00,000
An Internal Developer Platform is a system that makes the right thing
the easy thing. And makes the wrong thing require deliberate effort to do.

38
03:42:00,000 --> 03:48:00,000

39
03:48:00,000 --> 03:54:00,000
In the context of FinOps, the right thing means.

40
03:54:00,000 --> 04:00:00,000
Every new S3 bucket has a lifecycle policy.
Every new RDS instance is tagged with its schedule.

41
04:00:00,000 --> 04:06:00,000
Every new Kubernetes workload has appropriate resource requests.
Every new service uses Spot instances where appropriate.

42
04:06:00,000 --> 04:12:00,000
Every new ECR repository has a cleanup policy.

43
04:12:00,000 --> 04:18:00,000

44
04:18:00,000 --> 04:24:00,000
Before an IDP, a developer creates these resources manually.
They do what they know.

45
04:24:00,000 --> 04:30:00,000
If they do not know about lifecycle policies,
the bucket has no lifecycle policy.

46
04:30:00,000 --> 04:36:00,000
If they do not know about Spot tolerations,
the workload runs On-Demand.

47
04:36:00,000 --> 04:42:00,000
The cost controls depend entirely on what individual engineers
happen to know.

48
04:42:00,000 --> 04:48:00,000

49
04:48:00,000 --> 04:54:00,000
After an IDP, the developer clicks a button in a portal.
They answer five questions.

50
04:54:00,000 --> 05:00:00,000
Service name. Team. Expected traffic.
Database needed. Cache needed.

51
05:00:00,000 --> 05:06:00,000
The platform creates everything.
The S3 bucket already has a lifecycle policy.

52
05:06:00,000 --> 05:12:00,000
The RDS instance is already tagged.
The Helm chart already has Spot tolerations.

53
05:12:00,000 --> 05:18:00,000
The ECR repository already has a cleanup policy.
The developer never thought about any of it.

54
05:18:00,000 --> 05:24:00,000
They just shipped code.

55
05:24:00,000 --> 05:30:00,000
That is what we are building in Series seven through ten.

56
05:30:00,000 --> 05:36:00,000

57
05:36:00,000 --> 05:42:00,000
Before we build, let me explain the three failure modes of platform teams.
I have watched each of these play out multiple times.

58
05:42:00,000 --> 05:48:00,000

59
05:48:00,000 --> 05:54:00,000
Failure mode one. The Gatekeeper Platform.
The platform team controls all infrastructure. Developers file tickets.

60
05:54:00,000 --> 06:00:00,000
The platform team reviews, approves, implements.
Nothing happens without them.

61
06:00:00,000 --> 06:06:00,000
Result. Developers wait days or weeks for infrastructure changes.
They start working around the platform.

62
06:06:00,000 --> 06:12:00,000
They find ways to deploy directly.
Shadow infrastructure proliferates.

63
06:12:00,000 --> 06:18:00,000
The platform becomes irrelevant.
Developers hate the platform team.

64
06:18:00,000 --> 06:24:00,000
The signal. Your developers describe the platform team
as a bottleneck or the no team.

65
06:24:00,000 --> 06:30:00,000

66
06:30:00,000 --> 06:36:00,000
Failure mode two. The Invisible Platform.
No platform team exists. Every team builds their own tooling.

67
06:36:00,000 --> 06:42:00,000
Every service has its own deployment pipeline.
Every developer makes their own infrastructure decisions.

68
06:42:00,000 --> 06:48:00,000
Result. Ten teams, ten different CI/CD systems.
Ten different tagging strategies. Ten different cost profiles.

69
06:48:00,000 --> 06:54:00,000
Nobody can move between teams without a two-week ramp-up.
Security is inconsistent. FinOps is impossible.

70
06:54:00,000 --> 07:00:00,000
The bill is unpredictable.

71
07:00:00,000 --> 07:06:00,000
The signal. How do I deploy here? is a question that takes a week to answer
at your company.

72
07:06:00,000 --> 07:12:00,000

73
07:12:00,000 --> 07:18:00,000
Failure mode three. The Shiny Platform.
The platform team builds a beautiful developer portal.

74
07:18:00,000 --> 07:24:00,000
It has great UX, slick dashboards, amazing search.
Developers love the experience.

75
07:24:00,000 --> 07:30:00,000
But the golden paths inside the platform are poorly designed.
Resource requests are too high. No Spot tolerations.

76
07:30:00,000 --> 07:36:00,000
No lifecycle policies. The platform makes it easy to do things.
But easy to do expensive things.

77
07:36:00,000 --> 07:42:00,000
The signal. Your platform adoption is high
but your AWS bill is still out of control.

78
07:42:00,000 --> 07:48:00,000

79
07:48:00,000 --> 07:54:00,000
The platform in this course avoids all three.
It is self-service. No gatekeeper.

80
07:54:00,000 --> 08:00:00,000
It is universal. No invisible shadow infrastructure.
It is cost-encoded. The golden paths are built on everything
you learned in Series two through six.

81
08:00:00,000 --> 08:06:00,000

82
08:06:00,000 --> 08:12:00,000
Now let me introduce you to the team topologies framework.
Platform engineering does not work without the right team structure.

83
08:12:00,000 --> 08:18:00,000
The framework that has become the industry standard is Team Topologies
by Matthew Skelton and Manuel Pais.

84
08:18:00,000 --> 08:24:00,000

85
08:24:00,000 --> 08:30:00,000
Four team types.

86
08:30:00,000 --> 08:36:00,000
First, stream-aligned teams.
Your product teams. They build features, ship code, serve customers.

87
08:36:00,000 --> 08:42:00,000
They are aligned to a stream of work. A product area. A user journey.
A business capability.

88
08:42:00,000 --> 08:48:00,000
The financial-rag team and the riskoracle team
are stream-aligned teams.

89
08:48:00,000 --> 08:54:00,000
Stream-aligned teams should spend the vast majority of their time
on product work. Not on infrastructure decisions.

90
08:54:00,000 --> 09:00:00,000
Not on security reviews. Not on cost optimization.
The platform exists to remove that cognitive load.

91
09:00:00,000 --> 09:06:00,000

92
09:06:00,000 --> 09:12:00,000
Second, platform teams.
Build and maintain the Internal Developer Platform.

93
09:12:00,000 --> 09:18:00,000
Their job is to reduce cognitive load for stream-aligned teams.
They treat stream-aligned teams as their customers.

94
09:18:00,000 --> 09:24:00,000
They build products, not just tools.
They have a roadmap, user research, and adoption metrics.
Not just a ticket queue.

95
09:24:00,000 --> 09:30:00,000
The platform team in this course owns.
The developer portal. Backstage or Port.

96
09:30:00,000 --> 09:36:00,000
The golden path templates. Helm charts, Terraform modules,
CI/CD templates.

97
09:36:00,000 --> 09:42:00,000
The FinOps tooling. Kubecost dashboards, budget alerts,
chargeback reports.

98
09:42:00,000 --> 09:48:00,000
The cost controls. Lifecycle policies, reserved instances,
Karpenter configuration.

99
09:48:00,000 --> 09:54:00,000

100
09:54:00,000 --> 10:00:00,000
Third, enabling teams.
Temporarily embedded with stream-aligned teams to help them adopt
new practices.

101
10:00:00,000 --> 10:06:00,000
They run workshops. Write documentation. Answer questions.
They do not own systems. They transfer knowledge.

102
10:06:00,000 --> 10:12:00,000
In the context of this course, an enabling team would help
the financial-rag team migrate their existing workloads
to the golden path templates after the IDP is built.

103
10:12:00,000 --> 10:18:00,000

104
10:18:00,000 --> 10:24:00,000
Fourth, complicated-subsystem teams.
Own particularly complex parts of the system that require deep expertise.

105
10:24:00,000 --> 10:30:00,000
For riskoracle, the ML training infrastructure. Spot engineering,
checkpointing, GPU node pools.

106
10:30:00,000 --> 10:36:00,000
Might be owned by a complicated-subsystem team that provides it
as a service to other teams.

107
10:36:00,000 --> 10:42:00,000

108
10:42:00,000 --> 10:48:00,000
Now let me explain golden paths.
This is the core concept of platform engineering.

109
10:48:00,000 --> 10:54:00,000
A golden path is the well-maintained, well-documented,
well-supported way of doing something on your platform.

110
10:54:00,000 --> 11:00:00,000
It is the path the platform team promises to keep working,
keep secure, keep cost-optimized, and keep documented.

111
11:00:00,000 --> 11:06:00,000
The name comes from the idea that this is the paved road.
Smooth, fast, well-lit.

112
11:06:00,000 --> 11:12:00,000
Developers can go off-road if they want.
But if they do, they are on their own.

113
11:12:00,000 --> 11:18:00,000

114
11:18:00,000 --> 11:24:00,000
For deploying a new microservice,
the golden path at the end of this course includes.

115
11:24:00,000 --> 11:30:00,000
Language. Python 3.11. Platform-supported. Cheaper to debug.
Framework. FastAPI. Auto-instruments for Prometheus.

116
11:30:00,000 --> 11:36:00,000
Container. Multi-arch. Amd64 and arm64. Enables Graviton Spot instances.
Resource requests. Sized by traffic tier. Prevents over-provisioning.

117
11:36:00,000 --> 11:42:00,000
Spot tolerations. Applied for low and medium traffic.
Sixty to seventy percent compute savings.

118
11:42:00,000 --> 11:48:00,000
S3 bucket. Created with lifecycle policy. Automatic storage tiering.
RDS. Tagged with environment and schedule. Stop and start automation.

119
11:48:00,000 --> 11:54:00,000
ECR. Created with lifecycle policy. Automatic image cleanup.
Observability. OpenTelemetry auto-instrumentation.

120
11:54:00,000 --> 12:00:00,000
Cost-visible in Kubecost. Chargeback-ready.

121
12:00:00,000 --> 12:06:00,000

122
12:06:00,000 --> 12:12:00,000
A developer using this golden path does not make any of these decisions.
They just answer. What is your service name? Which team? What traffic level?

123
12:12:00,000 --> 12:18:00,000
The platform handles everything else.

124
12:18:00,000 --> 12:24:00,000

125
12:24:00,000 --> 12:30:00,000
Developers are allowed, and sometimes need, to go outside the golden path.
Three rules.

126
12:30:00,000 --> 12:36:00,000
One. Going outside the golden path means you own it yourself.
No platform support.

127
12:36:00,000 --> 12:42:00,000
Two. Going outside the golden path means you justify it
in an Architecture Decision Record. An ADR.

128
12:42:00,000 --> 12:48:00,000
Three. Going outside the golden path means your cost attribution
still applies. The platform will still show your team's spend
even if your infrastructure is non-standard.

129
12:48:00,000 --> 12:54:00,000
This is not restriction. It is clarity.
The platform does not prevent innovation.
It prevents accidental deviation from best practices.

130
12:54:00,000 --> 13:00:00,000

131
13:00:00,000 --> 13:06:00,000
Now let me help you choose between Backstage and Port.
Two platforms dominate the IDP space.

132
13:06:00,000 --> 13:12:00,000

133
13:12:00,000 --> 13:18:00,000
First, Backstage. Open source from Spotify.
You host it. You maintain it. You upgrade it. You build plugins for it.

134
13:18:00,000 --> 13:24:00,000
Strengths. Complete customization. You control every pixel.
Large community. Two thousand plus contributors.

135
13:24:00,000 --> 13:30:00,000
Adopted by Spotify, Netflix, Expedia, American Airlines.
Rich plugin ecosystem. GitHub, ArgoCD, Kubernetes, Grafana.

136
13:30:00,000 --> 13:36:00,000
PagerDuty, and one hundred fifty more. Free. No per-seat cost.

137
13:36:00,000 --> 13:42:00,000
Weaknesses. You own the infrastructure. PostgreSQL, hosting, upgrades.
Node.js and TypeScript expertise required for customization.

138
13:42:00,000 --> 13:48:00,000
Initial setup takes two to four weeks for a team new to Backstage.
Plugin quality varies significantly.

139
13:48:00,000 --> 13:54:00,000
Best for. Platform teams of three or more engineers.
Organizations that need deep customization.
Companies with existing TypeScript expertise.

140
13:54:00,000 --> 14:00:00,000

141
14:00:00,000 --> 14:06:00,000
Second, Port. Commercial SaaS. Managed IDP platform.
Port hosts it. Port upgrades it. You just configure it.

142
14:06:00,000 --> 14:12:00,000
Strengths. No infrastructure to maintain.
SOC2 compliant. Ninety-nine point nine percent SLA.

143
14:12:00,000 --> 14:18:00,000
Built-in integrations work out of the box.
GitHub, AWS, Kubernetes, ArgoCD.

144
14:18:00,000 --> 14:24:00,000
Scorecards for FinOps compliance. Is this service cost-optimized?
Faster time to value. Can have a working portal in hours.

145
14:24:00,000 --> 14:30:00,000
Strong RBAC. Developers see only their own team's resources.

146
14:30:00,000 --> 14:36:00,000
Weaknesses. Per-seat cost. Zero dollars for up to fifteen users.
Paid tiers above that.

147
14:36:00,000 --> 14:42:00,000
Less flexible than Backstage for deeply custom workflows.
Data lives in Port's infrastructure.
Relevant for compliance requirements.

148
14:42:00,000 --> 14:48:00,000
Best for. Platform teams of one to two engineers.
Companies that need to move fast.
Organizations without TypeScript or React expertise.

149
14:48:00,000 --> 14:54:00,000

150
14:54:00,000 --> 15:00:00,000
Here is the decision matrix.

151
15:00:00,000 --> 15:06:00,000
If your platform team size is three or more engineers,
choose Backstage. If one to two engineers, choose Port.

152
15:06:00,000 --> 15:12:00,000
If time to first working portal is okay with two to four weeks,
choose Backstage. If you need it this week, choose Port.

153
15:12:00,000 --> 15:18:00,000
If you need deep custom UI or workflows, choose Backstage.
If standard portal with configuration is fine, choose Port.

154
15:18:00,000 --> 15:24:00,000
If you have TypeScript expertise, choose Backstage.
If you do not, choose Port.

155
15:24:00,000 --> 15:30:00,000

156
15:30:00,000 --> 15:36:00,000
For this course, we build on Backstage.
It forces you to understand the underlying architecture.

157
15:36:00,000 --> 15:42:00,000
But every concept maps directly to Port.
At the end of each section, we note the Port equivalent.

158
15:42:00,000 --> 15:48:00,000

159
15:48:00,000 --> 15:54:00,000
Now let me introduce you to the Software Catalog.
The foundation of every IDP.

160
15:54:00,000 --> 16:00:00,000
It is a central registry of all your services, APIs, databases,
infrastructure components, and documentation.

161
16:00:00,000 --> 16:06:00,000

162
16:06:00,000 --> 16:12:00,000
Before the catalog, answering who owns the llm-ingest service
requires Slack messages, digging through Terraform state,
or asking the person who has been there longest.

163
16:12:00,000 --> 16:18:00,000
Before the catalog, what does this service depend on?
Is unanswerable without reading the code.

164
16:18:00,000 --> 16:24:00,000

165
16:24:00,000 --> 16:30:00,000
With the catalog. Every service has an owner.
Every service has a team.

166
16:30:00,000 --> 16:36:00,000
Every service shows its deployment status.
Every service shows its cost via Kubecost integration.

167
16:36:00,000 --> 16:42:00,000
Every service shows its documentation.
Every service shows what it depends on.

168
16:42:00,000 --> 16:48:00,000
Every service shows its SLO status.

169
16:48:00,000 --> 16:54:00,000

170
16:54:00,000 --> 17:00:00,000
The catalog entity is defined in a YAML file called catalog-info.yaml
at the root of each repository.

171
17:00:00,000 --> 17:06:00,000
Backstage discovers these files by scanning GitHub organizations
or from explicitly registered URLs.

172
17:06:00,000 --> 17:12:00,000

173
17:12:00,000 --> 17:18:00,000
Let me walk you through a real catalog-info.yaml for financial-rag-agent.

174
17:18:00,000 --> 17:24:00,000
The kind is Component. A deployable service.
The name is financial-rag-agent.

175
17:24:00,000 --> 17:30:00,000
The description explains what it does.
Annotations connect Backstage to external tools.

176
17:30:00,000 --> 17:36:00,000
github.com slash project-slug tells Backstage which GitHub repo.
argocd slash app-name tells ArgoCD integration.

177
17:36:00,000 --> 17:42:00,000
kubecost.com slash namespace tells Kubecost integration.
finops slash monthly-budget sets the cost budget.

178
17:42:00,000 --> 17:48:00,000
finops slash alert-thresholds sets budget alert levels.
prometheus.io slash rule connects to SLOs.

179
17:48:00,000 --> 17:54:00,000
pagerduty.com slash service-id connects to on-call.
backstage.io slash techdocs-ref points to documentation.

180
17:54:00,000 --> 18:00:00,000

181
18:00:00,000 --> 18:06:00,000
Tags describe the technology stack.
Python, FastAPI, RAG, LLM, pgvector, production.

182
18:06:00,000 --> 18:12:00,000
Links point to GitHub, ArgoCD, Grafana, Slack.
Spec defines the type, lifecycle, owner, and system.

183
18:12:00,000 --> 18:18:00,000
dependsOn lists what this service needs.
providesApis lists what this service offers.

184
18:18:00,000 --> 18:24:00,000

185
18:24:00,000 --> 18:30:00,000
There are also Resource entities for infrastructure.
API entities for API specifications.
Group and User entities for teams and people.

186
18:30:00,000 --> 18:36:00,000

187
18:36:00,000 --> 18:42:00,000
Now let's install Backstage.

188
18:42:00,000 --> 18:48:00,000
First, the prerequisites. Node.js version eighteen or higher.
Yarn package manager. PostgreSQL for catalog storage.

189
18:48:00,000 --> 18:54:00,000

190
18:54:00,000 --> 19:00:00,000
Run a PostgreSQL container in Docker for development.
docker run with name backstage-postgres, environment variables,
port 5432, postgres fifteen alpine.

191
19:00:00,000 --> 19:06:00,000

192
19:06:00,000 --> 19:12:00,000
Create a new Backstage app.
npx at backstage slash create-app at latest dash dash skip-install.

193
19:12:00,000 --> 19:18:00,000
When prompted, enter a name for the app. finops-idp.
Select PostgreSQL. Database host localhost. Database port 5432.

194
19:18:00,000 --> 19:24:00,000
Database user backstage. Database password backstage.

195
19:24:00,000 --> 19:30:00,000
cd finops-idp. yarn install.

196
19:30:00,000 --> 19:36:00,000

197
19:36:00,000 --> 19:42:00,000
Configure app-config.yaml.
Set the app title and base URL.

198
19:42:00,000 --> 19:48:00,000
Set the backend listen port and database connection.
Set GitHub integration with your token.

199
19:48:00,000 --> 19:54:00,000
Set catalog locations to scan your repositories.
Set Kubernetes plugin configuration.

200
19:54:00,000 --> 20:00:00,000
Set Kubecost plugin base URL.

201
20:00:00,000 --> 20:06:00,000

202
20:06:00,000 --> 20:12:00,000
Start Backstage.
export all the environment variables. POSTGRES_HOST, POSTGRES_PORT,
POSTGRES_USER, POSTGRES_PASSWORD, POSTGRES_DATABASE.

203
20:12:00,000 --> 20:18:00,000
export GITHUB_TOKEN, GITHUB_CLIENT_ID, GITHUB_CLIENT_SECRET.
yarn dev.

204
20:18:00,000 --> 20:24:00,000

205
20:24:00,000 --> 20:30:00,000
Open http://localhost:3000. You should see the Backstage homepage.
Navigate to Catalog. You will see the entities discovered
from your GitHub repositories.

